The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Ive matured playing Ranji, says Dhawan
                                                                                                                                                                                                       Ive matured playing Ranji, says Dhawan
            A STAFF REPORTER    
	Calcutta: The Indian Premier League is fast becoming a window of opportunity for the talented youngsters. The frustrating anonymity associated with the domestic structure is gone and players like Manpreet Singh Gony, Yo Mahesh, Shikhar Dhawan, Dinesh Salunkhe are household names not to mention of the Ashok Dindas and the Wriddhiman Sahas.         
	Delhi DareDevils Dhawan has been one of the consistent performers in their campaign. The lefthanded batsman, though, feels it is a culmination of a fruitful domestic season  in eight Ranji matches he scored 570 at an average of 43.84 while in the Duleep Trophy his unbeaten 94 helped North claim the title in the final.         
	The secret behind the success has been my good form this season. I was also very eager to grab the opportunity. I worked really hard during the off season on my technical aspects and made myself mentally stronger. Ive also matured during the four years Ive been playing Ranji, Dhawan told The Telegraph.         
	The financial rewards will also flow automatically. It is clear that players like Dhawan, with three half-centuries and an average above 50 in the IPL, will earn more than their minimum $50,000.         
	The 22-year-old loves to dominate the attack and has been forced to come down the order because of the presence of Virender Sehwag and Gautam Gambhir in the side. But he doesnt regret that.                                                                                                                          
